5:
Is this what you had in mind when
you asked for a first-aid station,
Liesel?
11:
Yes! It has beds and even a ROOF!
It's more than I could possibly ask
for—I could stay here for days while I
continue my healing.
16:
Having a roof seems like the bare
minimum to me, but okay...
18:
Still, I suppose it is impressive that
they managed to get a tent set up
here on the beach.
21:
It's important to be vigilant, even
when enjoying oneself. You never
know when disaster could strike.
22:
May the memories we make on this
sunny shore be as resplendent as
the stars.
27:
Hurrah!
You heard her, let's do as our Angel
says!
29:
Everyone, get in line!
If you start to feel sick, let us know
right away!
30:
Our Guardian Angel will save you!
The Stars'll guide us on the right
path!
34:
Great work, everyone. This is quite
the turnout.
39:
Indeed! We were able to help so
many different people today!
43:
So much for your vacation. You've
been working the whole time!
48:
Haha, that's Liesel for you—always
helping others.
51:
Awesome! This way we'll be able to
help even MORE people—
53:
Pardon me.
Are you the girl people are referring
to as the "Guardian Angel"?
55:
I'm one of the managers of Paradise
Isle. I wanted to speak with you
about this first-aid station you've
erected.
57:
Hey, what do you think you're doing,
Mr. Manager? You think you can just
come here and talk to our Guardian
Angel?
58:
Yeah, all you care about is
MONEY.
Don't you dare try to steal our Angel
away from us!
62:
Everyone, please calm down.
Disputes are best resolved through
discussion!
65:
My name is Liesel. May I ask what
this matter is about?
72:
So, you don't approve of this
first-aid station?
75:
I didn't say that—it's merely that... we
already have a hospital on this
island.
And you seem to be healing all our
patients.
78:
Which is bad for your hospital's
business.
81:
Huh? Why should we care about
some fancy hospital for rich folks?
82:
Yeah! You constantly refuse to treat
any of us locals!
84:
Unfortunately, our hospital doesn't
have the resources to
accommodate people who can't
pay for their own treatment.
92:
...It's as father said. I've failed again
to help those who are in the direst
need.
95:
I have a suggestion. What do you
think about potentially employing
these men to work at your hospital?
98:
Guardian Angel... Are you telling us
to work for this money-grubber?
99:
Won't we just end up running
errands for rich guys in suits?
102:
No—you will become guiding stars
yourselves.
105:
We saw many patients today. In
many cases, if we had waited to
take them to the hospital, we would
have been too late.
107:
In your current state, the hospital
lacks the resources to take an influx
of more seriously ill patients, doesn't
it?
109:
Are you suggesting that we hire
these men and use them to treat
patients from the beach?
111:
Yes. I think they're more than
capable of it.
114:
Hmm... I will have to think on this
proposal further. Let's put this
matter on hold and speak again
later.
120:
Guardian Angel... I can't believe you
would do something like this for us!
What an elaborate plan!
123:
It isn't elaborate—I'm merely doing
as my father told me.
126:
I need to help those who truly need
it—the poor and the desperate.
129:
It won't be simple, but I don't intend
on giving up easily!
131:
Because I believe.
I believe that the Light of the Stars
resides within us all. It gives us
strength.
134:
But, Guardian Angel... We... We can't
possibly be anything like you! We're
not worthy!
137:
You are.
You are capable of more than you
know!
138: You've helped me so much already!
140:
It is now your turn to become the
guiding Star for others! You will be
beacons in the dark!
149:
I think we did a pretty good job
today, don't you?
165:
Why don't I start with teaching them
how to heal? The more guiding
Stars, the better!
170:
Understood.
First, we should prepare a manual.
173:
Agreed! Let's go buy some
parchment and get to work!
